# Player Validation Rules

## Canonical function

Always use `BasicHelpers.is_valid_player(player)` to check whether a player object is usable.

```lua
-- bool-only (most common)
if not BasicHelpers.is_valid_player(player) then return end

-- with error message (use when the message is logged or surfaced to the caller)
local ok, err = BasicHelpers.is_valid_player(player)
if not ok then
  ErrorHandler.debug_log("...", { error = err })
  return false
end
```

The second return value (`string?`) is optional — callers that only check the boolean can ignore it.

## When a guard is necessary

Place a guard when the player reference arrives from an **untrusted source**:

- `game.players[event.player_index]` — index may be stale or the player may have disconnected
- `game.get_player(...)` — may return nil
- Public/remote API entry points — callers outside the mod cannot be trusted
- Functions annotated `LuaPlayer|nil` — nil is an explicit contract

## When a guard is redundant

Do **not** add a guard to a private helper that is only called from a single path that already validated the player immediately above. Examples of this redundant pattern:

```lua
-- BAD: on_some_event validates at line N, then calls private_fn which re-validates
local player = game.players[event.player_index]
if not BasicHelpers.is_valid_player(player) then return end
private_fn(player)  -- redundant guard inside private_fn is noise

-- GOOD: private helpers trust their callers; guards live at the boundary
```

## Inline guards

The raw inline form `if not player or not player.valid then` is acceptable **only** in files that do not import `BasicHelpers` and where adding the import would create a new dependency. In all other files use the canonical function.
